Can the euro be fixed?
Paris - German Finance Minister Wolfgang Schäuble recently put the option of Greece leaving the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal has sparked a big debate about the principles underlying the euro, the governance model of the euro, and the rationale for the euro's existence.
Two weeks before Schäuble's proposal, European leaders had already noted a report on the future of the euro written by European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debate over Greece has led many policymakers to believe it is necessary to return to the original starting point.
Meanwhile, citizens are questioning why they should share a single currency?
Does this make sense? Can there be consensus on Greece's future?
Currency is like a nation; it requires a myth to establish it.
Traditional wisdom holds that the euro was a political price Germany paid to France in order to achieve reunification.
In fact, German reunification was just the final step of an engineering project that had been taking shape in the 1980s to solve a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, considering them incompatible with the single market; at the same time, they were unwilling to retain a monetary system dominated by the German central bank in the long term.
A truly European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In hindsight, German reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When exchange rates were locked in 1999, Germany was overvalued and facing economic difficulties; France was undervalued and experiencing economic prosperity.
Over the following decade, imbalances gradually emerged between the resurgent Germany and countries that experienced credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the global financial crisis in 2008, these conditions became a breeding ground for a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would look like without the euro.
Would the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Would the German mark be overvalued again?
Would countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Would real estate bubbles emerge in Spain?
Will government reforms be more or less?
It is impossible to establish a baseline for reverse analysis to assess the impact of the euro.
But this is certainly not a reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the economic performance of the Eurozone has been disappointing, and its political institutions must be held responsible.
What is truly important is whether a common European currency will still be significant in the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of leaving the euro is unimaginably high (and if the disintegration of the Eurozone were to occur during a crisis, it would further increase the costs and exacerbate mutual resentment among participating countries).
Moreover, abolishing the euro could unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O’Rourke from Oxford University recently pointed out that this view is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to advising a couple to stay married simply because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still make sense?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
It was assumed that a monetary union would promote economic integration and consolidate long-term growth in Europe.
On the contrary, internal trade and investment growth in the eurozone have been mediocre, and the growth potential has actually been weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not gone further on the basis of monetary unity to build the eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead have tried to retain the remaining power they have.
This might make sense in political terms, but is economically futile: Europe's huge internal market is one of its main assets, so the opportunity to strengthen the internal market must never be wasted.
Secondly, people hoped that the euro would become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries could meet the necessary legal, market, and policy institutions).
However, according to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has basically been realized.
The euro's international use comes second only to the dollar, and this achievement helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an irrelevant entity.
Thirdly, people (not without naivety) believed that the institutions underlying the euro could improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if Europe's overall policy level was naturally higher than that of national policies.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test came: the Eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimensions of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimensions, and thus performed worse than the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further reforms of the policy regime are essential.
However, formulating and implementing a agenda requires a broad consensus on the nature of the problems.
The ongoing debates over the Greek issue indicate that Europe is still far from reaching an agreement: member countries have conflicting analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis, and thus their prescribed solutions are also conflicting.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, the governance of global diseases was greatly hindered by differing patterns of transmission among countries.
Countries favor collective action, but cannot form a consistent plan because they disagree on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the issue the Eurozone faces today.
Luckily, this problem is not unsolvable, as major reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the launch of a banking union have proven.
Inconsistencies have not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, which indicates that institutional governance is indeed important.
However, the fact that reforms and actions only began recently and were implemented under the pressure of a severe crisis makes us clearly aware of the difficulty of reaching consensus.
Europe can no longer delay or pretend any longer.
The Eurozone member states must establish a unified agenda on governance and political reform to transform the monetary union into a driver of prosperity, or else they will sink into recurring disputes and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and major reforms.
Now, all key stakeholders have the obligation to clearly define what they consider indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to trade for what they desire.
